Reward: 50-350+ points if accepted, depending on quality 
Issued: April 30, 2021 
Deadline: May 28 2021, 11:59 PM Pacific Standard Time. 
Description: Identify a place or object that was once damaging the environment around it, but has now been modified so that it is restoring it. Go to this place or object in person, and photograph the place with an ECO logo physically in frame to prove that you visited. Post that photo with a short history of the place, how it once damaged its environment, and how it was modified so that it now is restorative. Please post your history as a google doc with your Discord username as the first word. Examples might include mines, industrial facilities, prisons, former crime hotspots, garbage dumps, etc.
(Thanks to @Qubinets for this excellent bounty concept)
Please ask questions if confused.

Hi @Bryce  | Eco ! We need an object that is made from non-ecological to eco-friendly. Or is it suitable for an object in which the bad influence on nature has been suppressed, but it does not work now? (as the 4th nuclear reactor at the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant)
Both are acceptable.
The only thing that matters is visiting it, and explaining what happened.
Stories that include repurposing to be eco-friendly are more interesting generally, but that doesn't mean the simply defunct are boring.

#🏹research-bounty-b 
:eco: :eco: :eco:  **A Former Gas Plant is Blossoming** :eco: :eco: :eco: 

Here is my submission for the Eco Research Project. It's titled: **A Former Gas Plant is Blossoming**. I am reporting about an old gas plant that had a devastating impact on the environment as it produced a daily output of 50,000-100,000 m³ of gas from burning coal. After having ceased its operations, flowering meadows have been planted to support the biological diversity in the area. Here is the full report: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1olw-q-z0wE_tHrQWxcizjC9-Xs83A8rWyAmKORFA5jw/edit?usp=sharing. I visited the site in person and have included proof in the document. Please forgive me that I'm holding the logo upside down, I was a bit distracted by the rain 😆 I've added my name next to the logo for further proof.

Hi Bryce, we managed to collect some part of the diesel fuel, but unfortunately part of the diesel fuel passed under the protective pantons and has already got into the soil. Unfortunately, it makes no sense to talk about the quality of harvesting today, such disasters are practically irreversible. It is much more important to pay attention to the amount of the fine, it is equal to the damage caused and the cost of eliminating it. If this practice of fines appears at the legislative level, then repairs will cost less than a fine and this will change something. Official sources reported back in 2020 that 90% of the spilled fuel was collected, but I do not believe in this.
